  </style>

  <div class="article-header">
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#FAEEDA;color:#412402;">Beginner</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#EEEDFE;color:#26215C;">Atomic Structure</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="article-title">What is an atom?</h1>
    <div class="objective"><strong>Learning objective:</strong> Describe the structure of an atom and identify the three main particles inside it.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="vocab-box">
    <div class="vocab-title">Key vocabulary</div>
    <div class="vocab-grid">
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Atom</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">The smallest particle of an element that still has the properties of that element.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Nucleus</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">The dense center of an atom. Contains protons and neutrons.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Proton</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A positively charged particle found in the nucleus. Its number defines the element.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Neutron</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A particle with no charge found in the nucleus. Adds mass to the atom.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Electron</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">A negatively charged particle that moves around the nucleus in shells.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-word">Atomic number</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">The number of protons in an atom. Every element has a unique atomic number.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <a href="https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=what+is+an+atom+high+school+chemistry" target="_blank" class="video-link">
    <div class="video-icon">▶</div>
    <div class="video-title">Watch on YouTube</div>
    <div class="video-subtitle">Search: what is an atom high school chemistry</div>
  </a>

  <div class="facts-box">
    <div class="facts-title">Key facts</div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">All matter is made of atoms. Atoms are extremely small — one million atoms side by side would fit across a human hair.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">An atom has three types of particles: <strong>protons</strong> (positive charge), <strong>neutrons</strong> (no charge), and <strong>electrons</strong> (negative charge).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">Protons and neutrons are found in the <strong>nucleus</strong> at the center. Electrons move around the nucleus in <strong>shells</strong>.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">The number of protons is called the <strong>atomic number</strong>. It identifies the element — carbon always has 6, oxygen always has 8.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact">
      <div class="fact-dot"></div>
      <div class="fact-text">In a neutral atom, the number of protons equals the number of electrons. The charges balance out.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="summary-box">
    <div class="summary-title">Summary</div>
    <div class="summary-text">
      An atom is the basic building block of all matter. It has a nucleus containing protons and neutrons, with electrons moving around the outside in shells. The number of protons identifies the element — this is called the atomic number.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="topic-tags">
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#EEEDFE;color:#534AB7;">Atomic structure</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#FAEEDA;color:#633806;">Beginner</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Protons</span>
    <span class="topic-tag" style="background:#E6F1FB;color:#0C447C;">Electrons</span>
  </div>
